{"key":"processedPost-12855266","value":{"id":12855266,"first":12854320,"last":26399311,"when":1278419851,"utime":"07/06/10 03:37 PM","content":"Not so.<br /><br />Fine verm is superior to perlite sized chunks.&nbsp; <br /><br />One doesn't want 'dust', but fine verm, which is roughly the size of rye grass seed for example. Fine verm holds more moisture than course verm and also works much better as a filter at the top of the jar.&nbsp; It was fine verm that was used in the <a href=\"http://www.mushroomvideos.com/BRF-Pf-Tek\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer noopener\">brf tek videos</a>, so anyone can watch them and get an idea of the correct size.<br /><br />In addition, the 'pf tek' was not invented.&nbsp; Growers had been using vermiculite in substrates, and supplementing with cereal bran and flour for decades before pf attached his internet screen name from ADM to a process of using them in 1/2 pint jars.&nbsp; Saying he 'invented' the procedure is like saying 'so and so' invented growing on straw, and 'this or that' guy invented growing on manure, etc.&nbsp; Natural processes are not invented.&nbsp; He may have developed a procedure, aka 'tek', but it wasn't an invention.<br />RR","title":"Re: what grade vermiculite?"}}